The Agriculture Department confirmed Thursday that a deadening drought will curtail the Fall corn harvest by a third or more, resulting in higher retail food prices for months and years to come.
President Reagan has signed a $3.9 billion relief bill that will help farmers to survive to plant again next Spring.
Compared to 1987, corn production is down 34%, soybeans 23%, wheat 1%, oats 45%, barley 45%, sorghum 24%.
Ewen M. Wilson, the Agriculture department's chief economist, said that the United States might import some soybeans this year.